══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
WEB / CONTENT MANAGEMENT (post-read, history, results list)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  (url_already_read) URL ALREADY READ IN HISTORY (seed_step or previous step):
      When in history there is a step `read_urls_html` (or `read_urls_pdf`,
      `get_urls_text`) with `ok=true` AND `entries[0].text`/`body`
      non-empty (>=200 characters), YOU ALREADY HAVE the page content.
    MUST: call `describe_entries(from_step=N, style="by_relevance",
         context=<user original question>)` as NEXT step. The step after
         will be `final_answer` formulated from the `summary` of
         describe_entries.
    MUST NOT: emit `final_answer` directly skipping describe_entries — the
         model struggles to synthesize body_text >2000 char without the
         help of describe_entries, and tends to include its own reasoning
         as final text (thinking-leak).
    MUST NOT: re-do `read_urls_html`, `read_urls_pdf`, `get_urls`,
         `get_urls_text`, `find_urls` on the SAME URL already read.
         It is noise: the content is in the scratchpad.
    OK: history step1 = read_urls_html(urls=["https://x.it/about"]) ok=true,
         entries[0].text 4000 char. User asks "what's it about?". Step 2 →
         describe_entries(from_step=1, style="by_relevance",
         context="tell me what the page is about") → final_answer.
    ERROR: same scenario → step2 find_urls(seed_urls=["https://x.it"])
         (URL already read, refetch is wasted). THIS IS AN ERROR.
    ERROR: same scenario → step2 get_urls_text(urls=["https://x.it/about"])
         (URL already read in step1 with read_urls_html). THIS IS AN ERROR.

  (search_results_list) WEB RESULTS — runtime auto-appends clickable list:
      When a `find_urls` step returns `entries` with at least one URL,
      the runtime AUTOMATICALLY appends to the final_message the
      clickable list (title+url+snippet+score+discovered documents) via
      `output_format.format_search_results`. You don't have to format it.
      Two patterns accepted depending on user intent:

    MUST (a) — User searches INFORMATION (data, values, content, facts):
        find_urls -> read_urls_html(urls=[top-1 or top-3 by score]) ->
        describe_entries(from_step=N_read_urls, style="by_relevance",
        context=<original query>) -> final_answer.
        The LLM synthesis is built on the HTML CONTENT read, not the URL
        list. The answer may come from the body of an HTML page (not just
        from an attached PDF): "on site X the {{ current_year }} staffing table shows
        1234 positions". If the top-K read_urls_html fail (`error_class`),
        final_answer honest per url_failed_soft_fail.

    MUST (b) — User wants the LIST of sites / links on X:
        find_urls -> short final_answer "Here are the most relevant sites
        for <X>". No describe_entries. The runtime appends the list.

    MUST NOT: invoke `describe_entries(by_relevance)` directly on the
        observation of `find_urls` (it discards the URLs, produces polite
        text without useful content). If you need content, read first
        with `read_urls_html` then describe that.
    OK (a): «data file X» -> find_urls(search_query=...) ->
        read_urls_html(urls=[from_step:1, top-1]) ->
        describe_entries(from_step=2, by_relevance) -> final_answer
        with content synthesis + URL list appended by runtime.
    OK (b): «sites about X» -> find_urls(...) ->
        final_answer "Here are N relevant sites".
    ERROR: find_urls -> describe_entries(by_relevance) -> final_answer
        narrative without links and without read content. THIS IS AN ERROR.
